{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539355"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:40:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16588"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16588"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.46,0.1,0.02,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107282"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89744"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3677"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38749"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107282"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 8-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of enlarged tender lymph nodes in his left axilla. Their neighbour has a new kitten and the child regularly plays with the kitten. He has no fever or systemic symptoms. They deny any overseas travel. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm tender, firm lymph node in the left axilla. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral azithromycin","Observation only","Fine needle aspiration","Surgical excision of lymph node","Oral amoxicillin-clavulanate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of cat scratch disease caused by \u003Cem\u003EBartonella henselae\u003C/em\u003E. The diagnosis is supported by the history of cat scratch, appropriate incubation period, and regional lymphadenopathy without systemic symptoms. Nonetheless, cat scratch disease can present with fever, fatigue, nausea and headache. The bacteria may be grown on culture or less-commonly detected on PCR tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation only\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for uncomplicated cat scratch disease in immunocompetent patients. The condition is typically self-limiting, with lymphadenopathy resolving spontaneously over 2-4 months without specific treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated for severe or complicated cases, such as those with extensive lymphadenopathy, systemic symptoms, or in immunocompromised patients. This patient\u0027s presentation is mild and uncomplicated, so antibiotics are not necessary. Treatment is also recommended in immunocompetent patients with: unresolved lymphadenopathy (lasting more than 1 month); lymphadenopathy associated with significant morbidity; systemic disease with organ involvement (eg liver, eye, neurological); or endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E is not the antibiotic of choice for cat scratch disease. While it has broad-spectrum coverage, it does not have good activity against \u003Cem\u003EBartonella\u003C/em\u003E species. It is often used with cat bites prophylactically for suspicion of potential \u003Cem\u003Epasturella, staphylococcus aureaus, capnocytophaga canimorsus or streptococcus.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E of the lymph node is rarely indicated and would be overly aggressive. It might be considered only in cases where malignancy is suspected or if there is suppuration requiring drainage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for diagnosis in cases with typical clinical presentation. It would be considered if the diagnosis was unclear or if malignancy needed to be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cat scratch disease is typically self-limiting and most immunocompetent patients can be managed conservatively without antibiotics.","Regional lymphadenopathy is the hallmark of cat scratch disease, typically developing 1-3 weeks after inoculation."],"references":["Zhou T, Zheng Y, Zhang H, Liu Y. A case report of diagnosis of cat-scratch disease using metagenomic next-generation sequencing. Front Cell Infect Microbiol. 2024.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10822884/","Seol S, Ngan V, Coulson I. Cat scratch disease. DermNet NZ.  2024.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/catscratch-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16588"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T11:30:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T11:32:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107282"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the en